We must “build” the balance‐sheet “Interest Receivable” amount by “netting” (i.e. summing) all transactions that affect that account during the period. In our file the “Interest Receivables” are recorded on many different dates (all with type “Interest Receivables”). Note that no “Interest Receivables” entry appears among the “Initial” entries so (as in the sample solution) we assume that the beginning balance is zero.

Step‐by‐step we “pick” each row whose type is “Interest Receivables” and add its amount (using the “recorded_amount” value here). For example, the first such row (dated 2024‑01‑01) is 418.30, the next row on 2024‑01‑02 is 418.30 and so on. (In our dataset the amounts are very similar – about 418 on early January then, toward the end of January and into February, they are “mildly” smaller – on 2024‑01‑29 the amount becomes 399.97 and later on 2024‑01‑31 it drops to roughly 382.17; in February the values are around 382.17 or just a few pennies under 382.) 

When you add up all 36 “Interest Receivables” transactions (from 2024‑01‑01 up to 2024‑02‑05) you get a final total of about 14,796.43.

Since no interest receivable existed in the opening (“Initial…”) entries, the beginning (initial) balance is 0.00.

Thus, the solution is as follows:

{
  "solution": {
    "Interest Receivable Initial Value": "0.00",
    "Interest Receivable End Value": "14796.43"
  }
}
